and Accommodation: Vertov’s Three Songs of Lenin (1934) as a Stalinist Film -- tConcluding Addendum: The Tradition of Experimentation in Russian Culture and the Russian Avant-Garde -- tList of Contributors -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Russian avant-garde was a composite of antagonistic groups who wished to overthrow the basic aesthetics of classical realism. Modernism was the totality of these numerous aesthetic theories, which achieved a measure of coherence immediately after the First World War. This collection of essays by leading scholars examines the major figures, movements, and manifestos of the period. Scholarly attention is given to literature, visual arts, cinema, and theatre in an attempt to capture the complex nature of the modernist movement in Russia. This book would be especially relevant for university courses on the Russian twentieth century as well as for those looking for a comprehensive approach to the various movements and artistic expressions that constitute the Russian avant-garde.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArts, Russiany20th century. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zRussiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aExperimental theaterzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aModernism (Art)zRussiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aModernism (Art)zSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aModernism (Literature)zRussiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aModernism (Literature)zSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aRadicalism in art. 0aRadicalism in literature. 7aART / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aBasner, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBogdanov, Aleksandr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc